1
00:00:00,140 --> 00:00:05,780
In this video, we are going to learn how to run Docker Compose within the Visual Studio in order to

2
00:00:05,780 --> 00:00:10,100
set up RabbitMQ, which is a crucial component for asynchronous communication.

3
00:00:10,100 --> 00:00:15,710
So please open the Visual Studio and let's getting started with Docker Compose in Visual Studio.

4
00:00:15,710 --> 00:00:22,340
So you can see that under the our microservice solution we have a Docker compose file in the root folder.

5
00:00:22,340 --> 00:00:28,190
If you right click the docker compose and set a startup project, you can see that the Docker Compose

6
00:00:28,190 --> 00:00:30,590
learning profile comes into Visual Studio.

7
00:00:30,590 --> 00:00:34,940
So now this will be run the docker compose using the Visual Studio.

8
00:00:34,940 --> 00:00:39,020
But this time I'm going to run Docker compose without debugging.

9
00:00:39,020 --> 00:00:44,150
Here you can see that next to Docker Compose learning profile you can see the start without debugging

10
00:00:44,150 --> 00:00:45,530
option in Visual Studio.

11
00:00:45,530 --> 00:00:48,290
So we will start without debugging in Docker Compose.

12
00:00:48,290 --> 00:00:51,920
That means this will be run the docker compose project without debugging.

13
00:00:51,920 --> 00:00:55,070
So hitting this button and this will be start to running.

14
00:00:55,070 --> 00:01:00,860
And this process may take a few minutes during the first run as Docker pulls and build the necessary

15
00:01:00,860 --> 00:01:01,580
images.

16
00:01:01,580 --> 00:01:06,410
So when the first time running, it takes some time to spin up RabbitMQ images.

17
00:01:06,410 --> 00:01:13,490
Because when we give the management image for RabbitMQ, it does not the base RabbitMQ image and management

18
00:01:13,490 --> 00:01:15,200
dashboard image altogether.

19
00:01:15,200 --> 00:01:17,840
Here you can see the docker compose Yaml file.

20
00:01:17,840 --> 00:01:23,480
We give the image name as a management RabbitMQ that includes the base image Erlang and the management

21
00:01:23,510 --> 00:01:24,110
dashboard.

22
00:01:24,110 --> 00:01:28,190
So this is the overall HTML file that we have configured in the last time.

23
00:01:28,190 --> 00:01:30,980
So you can see the progress in the output.

24
00:01:30,980 --> 00:01:36,020
And also we can confirm the created image from the Docker desktop.

25
00:01:36,020 --> 00:01:39,470
Here you can see the Docker compose has started successfully.

26
00:01:39,470 --> 00:01:44,450
And also all microservices started successfully without debugging.

27
00:01:44,450 --> 00:01:50,300
And if you scroll down you can see the message broker is started successfully for the RabbitMQ management

28
00:01:50,300 --> 00:01:50,750
image.

29
00:01:50,750 --> 00:01:53,150
This is our message broker container.

30
00:01:53,150 --> 00:01:59,690
If you open the container, you can see the logs are created successfully and that means we are ready

31
00:01:59,690 --> 00:02:02,930
to use these message broker as a asynchronous communication.

32
00:02:02,930 --> 00:02:06,200
So now we can examine the RabbitMQ Docker image.

33
00:02:06,200 --> 00:02:12,110
If you scroll the right hand side you can see that we have exposed the RabbitMQ port numbers in our

34
00:02:12,110 --> 00:02:13,010
local computer.

35
00:02:13,010 --> 00:02:20,030
And RabbitMQ management image has two port numbers, the one for the actual RabbitMQ image and another

36
00:02:20,030 --> 00:02:21,980
for the RabbitMQ management dashboard.

37
00:02:21,980 --> 00:02:30,680
So if I hit the 15672 port number, you can see that this will be redirecting to us RabbitMQ management

38
00:02:30,680 --> 00:02:31,190
dashboard.

39
00:02:31,190 --> 00:02:33,260
Here you can see the username and password.

40
00:02:33,260 --> 00:02:38,000
You can give the guest and guest as a username and password and click the login button.

41
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:44,150
So this is the our RabbitMQ management dashboard that we can log in the credentials with the guest and

42
00:02:44,150 --> 00:02:44,540
guest.

43
00:02:44,540 --> 00:02:50,990
And here you can see the main sections including the connections channels exchange queues and streams

44
00:02:50,990 --> 00:02:51,950
and the admin.

45
00:02:51,950 --> 00:02:59,150
So exchange are representing the routes messages between the queues and the queues and streams representing

46
00:02:59,150 --> 00:03:02,180
the storing messages that are waiting to be processed.

47
00:03:02,180 --> 00:03:05,750
And we have also topics for routing mechanism for messages.

48
00:03:05,750 --> 00:03:10,580
So if you scroll down in the overview page you can see that we have a node section.

49
00:03:10,580 --> 00:03:16,520
And under the node section we will identify the node name as a RabbitMQ message queue.

50
00:03:16,550 --> 00:03:20,180
Here you can see that this is the rabbit at e-commerce MQ.

51
00:03:20,210 --> 00:03:25,610
As you remember that e-commerce MQ is our hostname when we are configuring our Docker compose.

52
00:03:25,610 --> 00:03:27,710
And this is the our node definition.

53
00:03:27,710 --> 00:03:32,300
And if you scroll down you can see the listening ports in different protocols.

54
00:03:32,300 --> 00:03:34,340
Here you can see the Amqp protocol.

55
00:03:34,340 --> 00:03:37,610
The port number is default port number for the RabbitMQ image.

56
00:03:37,610 --> 00:03:42,650
And this is the Http protocol that we are going to use for the RabbitMQ management dashboard.

57
00:03:42,650 --> 00:03:44,960
This is 15672.

58
00:03:44,960 --> 00:03:49,400
And these are the other configurations in the RabbitMQ overview section.

59
00:03:49,400 --> 00:03:54,740
So as you can see that we have successfully run the RabbitMQ using the Docker compose in Visual Studio.

60
00:03:54,740 --> 00:03:59,570
And we have verified the RabbitMQ setup through the Docker desktop and the management dashboard.

